<div class="works-gallery">

  <div class="work-card">
    <%= image_tag "work1.jpg", class: "work-card-image" %>
    <h3 class="work-card-title">Judith Slaying Holofernes</h3>
    <p class="work-card-meta">1614–1620 • Oil on canvas</p>
    <p class="work-card-text">
      Perhaps her most famous painting: a scene of dramatic action, violence,
      and female agency rendered with extraordinary realism.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="work-card">
    <%= image_tag "work2.jpg", class: "work-card-image" %>
    <h3 class="work-card-title">Susanna and the Elders</h3>
    <p class="work-card-meta">1610 • Oil on canvas</p>
    <p class="work-card-text">
      Painted at only seventeen, this work already shows Artemisia’s
      psychological depth and empathy toward her female subjects.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="work-card">
    <%= image_tag "work3.jpg", class: "work-card-image" %>
    <h3 class="work-card-title">Self-Portrait as the Allegory of Painting</h3>
    <p class="work-card-meta">1638–39 • Oil on canvas</p>
    <p class="work-card-text">
      A bold statement of artistic identity: Artemisia portrays herself as
      “La Pittura,” the very personification of painting.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="work-card">
    <%= image_tag "work4.jpg", class: "work-card-image" %>
    <h3 class="work-card-title">Jael and Sisera</h3>
    <p class="work-card-meta">1620 • Oil on canvas</p>
    <p class="work-card-text">
      A powerful depiction of determination and justice, full of baroque
      tension and intensity.
    </p>
  </div>

</div>
